FLASHCARDS.push(
  // g10i-04-1 — Coastal Processes
  {id:"g10fc-04-1-1", islandId:"g10i-04-1", front:"Compare constructive and destructive waves.",
   back:"Constructive waves:\n• Low wave height, long wavelength\n• Strong swash pushes material up the beach; weak backwash\n• Build up the beach through deposition\n• Typically 6–8 waves per minute\n• Common in calm weather and sheltered bays\n\nDestructive waves:\n• High wave height, short wavelength\n• Weak swash; strong backwash pulls material down the beach\n• Erode the beach and remove material\n• Typically 10–14 waves per minute\n• Common during storms and along exposed coastlines\n\nThe balance between constructive and destructive waves determines whether a beach grows or shrinks.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-1-2", islandId:"g10i-04-1", front:"Describe the four processes of coastal erosion.",
   back:"1. Hydraulic action — the force of waves hitting the cliff compresses air into cracks. When the wave retreats, the compressed air expands explosively, weakening the rock.\n\n2. Abrasion — waves pick up rocks and hurl them at the cliff face, wearing it away like sandpaper. This is most effective during storms.\n\n3. Attrition — rocks carried by the waves collide with each other, becoming smaller and rounder over time. This does not erode the cliff but breaks down beach material.\n\n4. Solution (corrosion) — slightly acidic seawater dissolves soluble rocks such as chalk and limestone.\n\nHydraulic action and abrasion cause the most cliff erosion.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-1-3", islandId:"g10i-04-1", front:"Explain the difference between weathering and mass movement at the coast.",
   back:"Weathering is the in-situ breakdown of rock (it does not involve movement):\n• Mechanical (physical) — freeze-thaw: water enters cracks, freezes, expands (9%) and forces the crack wider. Repeated cycles shatter the rock.\n• Chemical — rainwater (slightly acidic) reacts with minerals in rock, weakening and dissolving them.\n• Biological — plant roots grow into cracks, widening them; burrowing animals weaken the rock.\n\nMass movement is the downhill movement of material under gravity:\n• Rockfall — fragments of rock break away from a cliff face and fall to the base.\n• Landslide — a large block of rock slides rapidly downslope along a weak plane.\n• Slumping — saturated clay or soft rock rotates and slides down a curved surface. Common after heavy rain.\n\nWeathering weakens the cliff; mass movement moves the weakened material.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-1-4", islandId:"g10i-04-1", front:"What is longshore drift and how does it work?",
   back:"Longshore drift is the movement of sediment along a coastline by wave action.\n\nProcess:\n1. Waves approach the beach at an angle (determined by the prevailing wind direction).\n2. The swash carries sediment up the beach at this angle.\n3. The backwash drags sediment straight back down the beach under gravity (at right angles to the shoreline).\n4. This creates a zigzag movement of sediment along the coast.\n\nLongshore drift is responsible for the formation of spits, bars and the redistribution of beach material. Groynes are often built to interrupt longshore drift and trap sediment, keeping beaches wide for tourism and coastal protection.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-1-5", islandId:"g10i-04-1", front:"How does rock type influence the rate of coastal erosion?",
   back:"Rock type is a key factor controlling erosion rates:\n\nResistant (hard) rock — granite, basite, limestone:\n• Eroded slowly\n• Forms headlands that jut out into the sea\n• Creates steep, rugged cliffs\n\nLess resistant (soft) rock — clay, sand, shale:\n• Eroded quickly\n• Forms bays where the sea has cut into the coast\n• Creates low, gentle cliffs that are prone to slumping\n\nDiscordant coastlines: rock types run perpendicular to the coast, creating alternating headlands and bays.\nConcordant coastlines: rock types run parallel to the coast; if the resistant outer layer is breached, rapid erosion of the softer rock behind occurs (e.g. Lulworth Cove, Dorset).\n\nJoints, faults and bedding planes also create weaknesses that accelerate erosion.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // g10i-04-2 — Coastal Landforms
  {id:"g10fc-04-2-1", islandId:"g10i-04-2", front:"Explain the formation of headlands and bays.",
   back:"Headlands and bays form on coastlines with alternating bands of resistant and less resistant rock running perpendicular to the sea (discordant coastline).\n\n1. Waves attack the coastline and erode softer rock more quickly.\n2. The softer rock is worn back to form a bay — a curved indentation with a beach.\n3. The harder rock is more resistant and erodes more slowly, remaining as a headland jutting out into the sea.\n4. Refraction causes waves to curve around headlands, concentrating erosion on their exposed sides.\n5. The bays are sheltered, so constructive waves deposit sediment, forming beaches.\n\nOver time, headlands are gradually eroded back, eventually straightening the coastline.\n\nExample: Swanage Bay (clay) and Ballard Point headland (chalk), Dorset.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-2-2", islandId:"g10i-04-2", front:"Describe the sequence of erosion from cave to arch to stack to stump.",
   back:"This sequence occurs on headlands exposed to powerful wave erosion:\n\n1. Cave — waves attack a weakness (joint or fault) in the headland by hydraulic action and abrasion. Over time, a cave is hollowed out.\n2. Arch — if caves develop on both sides of a narrow headland, they may eventually break through to form an arch.\n3. Stack — the roof of the arch is weakened by weathering and wave erosion. It eventually collapses, leaving an isolated column of rock — a stack.\n4. Stump — the base of the stack is undercut by wave erosion. The stack collapses to leave a low, flat stump, often only visible at low tide.\n\nExample: Old Harry Rocks, Dorset — a chalk stack and stump on Ballard Point headland.\n\nThe entire sequence may take thousands of years.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-2-3", islandId:"g10i-04-2", front:"Explain the formation of a cliff and wave-cut platform.",
   back:"Cliffs and wave-cut platforms form through the following process:\n\n1. Waves attack the base of a cliff between the high and low tide marks.\n2. Hydraulic action and abrasion create a wave-cut notch — a small indentation at the cliff base.\n3. As the notch deepens, the rock above is left unsupported.\n4. Eventually, the overhanging rock collapses under its own weight.\n5. The fallen debris is broken up and removed by waves.\n6. This process repeats, and the cliff retreats inland.\n7. The flat rocky platform left behind at the base of the retreating cliff is the wave-cut platform.\n\nWave-cut platforms are gently sloping, rocky surfaces exposed at low tide. They grow wider as the cliff retreats further.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-2-4", islandId:"g10i-04-2", front:"Describe how a spit is formed.",
   back:"A spit is a long, narrow ridge of sand or shingle extending from the coastline into the sea, often with a curved end.\n\nFormation:\n1. Longshore drift transports sediment along the coast.\n2. Where the coastline changes direction (e.g. at a river mouth or estuary), sediment continues to be deposited in the original direction of drift.\n3. The deposited material extends into the sea as a spit.\n4. The end of the spit may be curved by waves approaching from a different direction (secondary wind/wave direction).\n5. Behind the spit, sheltered water allows mud and silt to accumulate, forming saltmarshes.\n\nSpits grow longer over time but rarely extend across an entire bay because river currents prevent complete closure.\n\nExample: Spurn Head, Humber Estuary.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-2-5", islandId:"g10i-04-2", front:"What is the difference between a spit, a bar and a tombolo?",
   back:"Spit — a ridge of sediment extending from the coast into the sea, attached to the land at one end. Formed by longshore drift where the coastline changes direction. Often has a curved end and saltmarshes behind it. Example: Spurn Head.\n\nBar — forms when a spit extends completely across a bay, cutting off the water behind it. The trapped water becomes a lagoon. Example: Slapton Ley, Devon.\n\nTombolo — a bar of sediment that connects an island to the mainland. Formed by deposition between the island and the coast. Example: Chesil Beach connecting the Isle of Portland to the Dorset coast.\n\nAll three are depositional landforms created by longshore drift.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // g10i-04-3 — Coastal Management
  {id:"g10fc-04-3-1", islandId:"g10i-04-3", front:"Describe hard engineering methods of coastal management.",
   back:"Sea walls:\n• Concrete or rock barriers built at the cliff base\n• Reflect wave energy; prevent erosion\n• Expensive (£5,000–10,000 per metre); can be visually intrusive\n\nGroynes:\n• Wooden or rock barriers built perpendicular to the coast\n• Trap sediment carried by longshore drift, widening the beach\n• £5,000–10,000 each; starve beaches further along the coast of sediment\n\nRock armour (rip-rap):\n• Large boulders placed at the cliff base\n• Absorb wave energy; cheaper than sea walls (~£3,000 per metre)\n• Can look ugly and are hazardous to walk on\n\nGabions:\n• Wire cages filled with rocks, placed at the cliff base\n• Absorb wave energy; relatively cheap (~£100 per metre)\n• Short lifespan (5–10 years); unattractive", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-3-2", islandId:"g10i-04-3", front:"Describe soft engineering methods of coastal management.",
   back:"Beach nourishment:\n• Sand or shingle is added to the beach from elsewhere (often dredged offshore)\n• Widens the beach, which absorbs wave energy and protects the cliff\n• Looks natural; benefits tourism\n• Needs topping up regularly; expensive long-term (~£3,000 per metre per year)\n\nDune regeneration:\n• Replanting marram grass on sand dunes to stabilise them\n• Fencing protects dunes from trampling\n• Cheap; maintains natural appearance\n• Dunes are fragile and take years to establish\n\nManaged retreat:\n• Allowing the sea to flood low-value coastal land\n• Creates natural habitats (saltmarshes) that absorb wave energy\n• Controversial: landowners lose property; compensation required\n• Long-term, sustainable approach", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-3-3", islandId:"g10i-04-3", front:"Describe the coastal management case study: the Holderness Coast.",
   back:"The Holderness Coast, East Yorkshire, is one of the fastest-eroding coastlines in Europe — retreating 1–2 metres per year.\n\nWhy it erodes so fast:\n• Made of soft boulder clay, easily eroded by hydraulic action and abrasion\n• Exposed to powerful waves from the North Sea with a long fetch\n• Heavy rainfall causes slumping of saturated clay\n\nManagement conflicts:\n• Mappleton: rock armour and groynes protect the village but starve beaches to the south of sediment, increasing erosion elsewhere.\n• Hornsea: sea wall and groynes protect the town; undefended areas either side erode faster.\n• Some areas (e.g. Easington Gas Terminal) have significant protection; nearby villages are left undefended.\n\nKey issue: protecting one area often transfers the problem to neighbouring stretches of coast. This is the dilemma of coastal management.", difficulty:2, category:"case-study"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-3-4", islandId:"g10i-04-3", front:"What is Shoreline Management Planning?",
   back:"A Shoreline Management Plan (SMP) is a government strategy that divides the coastline into management units and decides the best approach for each:\n\nFour options:\n1. Hold the line — maintain or improve existing defences (e.g. major settlements)\n2. Advance the line — build new defences seaward of the existing coastline (rare; very expensive)\n3. Managed realignment — allow controlled flooding/erosion of low-value land to create natural defences\n4. No active intervention — let natural processes continue; no new defences built\n\nSMPs balance:\n• Economic value — is the area worth protecting?\n• Environmental impact — will defences damage habitats?\n• Social factors — do communities rely on the coastal land?\n• Cost-benefit analysis — does the cost of defence outweigh the value protected?\n\nSMPs are controversial because some communities feel abandoned by 'no active intervention' decisions.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-3-5", islandId:"g10i-04-3", front:"Evaluate the effectiveness of coastal management at the Holderness Coast.",
   back:"Effective aspects:\n+ Mappleton's rock armour and groynes have protected the village since 1991\n+ Hornsea's sea wall has prevented major erosion of the town centre\n+ Bridlington's defences protect a significant tourist economy\n\nLimitations:\n− Protecting one settlement starves neighbouring areas of sediment, accelerating erosion there\n− Undefended villages (e.g. Skipsea) continue to lose homes and farmland\n− The soft boulder clay is extremely difficult to protect cost-effectively\n− Managed retreat would be more sustainable but is politically difficult\n\nConclusion: current management protects economically important areas but creates inequalities. A more integrated approach — combining hard defences for key settlements with managed retreat for low-value areas — would be more sustainable but requires difficult decisions about which communities to protect.", difficulty:3, category:"evaluation"},

  // g10i-04-4 — Erosional Coastal Landforms
  {id:"g10fc-04-4-1", islandId:"g10i-04-4", front:"Name and describe the four processes of coastal erosion.",
   back:"1. Hydraulic action — the force of waves compresses air into cracks in the cliff. When the wave retreats, the compressed air expands explosively, weakening and breaking the rock.\n\n2. Abrasion — waves pick up rocks and hurl them at the cliff face, wearing it away like sandpaper. Most effective during storms.\n\n3. Attrition — rocks carried by the waves collide with each other, becoming smaller and rounder over time. This breaks down beach material rather than eroding the cliff.\n\n4. Solution (corrosion) — slightly acidic seawater dissolves soluble rocks such as chalk and limestone.\n\nHydraulic action and abrasion cause the most cliff erosion.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-4-2", islandId:"g10i-04-4", front:"Explain how headlands and bays form through differential erosion.",
   back:"Headlands and bays form on a discordant coastline, where alternating bands of hard and soft rock run perpendicular to the sea.\n\n1. Waves attack the coastline and erode the softer rock more quickly (differential erosion).\n2. The soft rock is worn back to form a curved bay, often with a beach.\n3. The harder, more resistant rock erodes slowly and is left jutting out as a headland.\n4. Wave refraction then bends waves around the headland, concentrating erosion on it.\n5. The bays are sheltered, so constructive waves deposit sediment to form beaches.\n\nOver time the headlands are eroded and the coastline gradually straightens.\n\nExample: Swanage Bay (clay) and Ballard Point headland (chalk), Dorset.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-4-3", islandId:"g10i-04-4", front:"Describe the sequence cracks → caves → arches → stacks → stumps.",
   back:"This sequence occurs on headlands exposed to powerful wave erosion:\n\n1. Cracks — waves attack lines of weakness (joints and faults) in the headland by hydraulic action and abrasion.\n2. Caves — the cracks are widened and deepened into caves.\n3. Arches — if caves form on both sides of a narrow headland, they may break through to form an arch.\n4. Stacks — the arch roof is weakened by weathering and wave erosion until it collapses, leaving an isolated column of rock called a stack.\n5. Stumps — the base of the stack is undercut by wave erosion; the stack collapses to leave a low, flat stump, often only visible at low tide.\n\nExample: Old Harry Rocks, Dorset. The sequence may take thousands of years.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-4-4", islandId:"g10i-04-4", front:"Explain how a wave-cut platform forms.",
   back:"Wave-cut platforms form as a cliff retreats:\n\n1. Waves attack the base of the cliff between the high and low tide marks.\n2. Hydraulic action and abrasion erode a wave-cut notch at the base.\n3. As the notch deepens, the rock above is left unsupported (an overhang).\n4. Eventually the overhang collapses under its own weight.\n5. The fallen debris is broken up by attrition and removed by waves.\n6. This process repeats and the cliff retreats inland.\n7. The flat, gently sloping rocky surface left at the base of the retreating cliff is the wave-cut platform.\n\nWave-cut platforms are exposed at low tide and grow wider as the cliff retreats further.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-4-5", islandId:"g10i-04-4", front:"Why does wave refraction concentrate erosion on headlands?",
   back:"Wave refraction is the bending of waves as they approach an irregular coastline.\n\n1. As a wave nears a headland, the part of the wave over the shallow water at the headland slows down due to friction with the sea bed.\n2. The part of the wave still in deeper water (over the bays) continues at full speed.\n3. This makes the wave bend, or refract, so that wave energy is focused on the sides of the headland.\n4. Concentrated energy means more erosion on the headland (forming caves, arches and stacks).\n5. In the bays, wave energy is spread out and weakened, so deposition occurs and beaches form.\n\nRefraction therefore explains why headlands are eroded while bays are sheltered.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // g10i-04-5 — Depositional Coastal Landforms
  {id:"g10fc-04-5-1", islandId:"g10i-04-5", front:"Explain how longshore drift transports sediment along a coast.",
   back:"Longshore drift moves sediment along a coastline by wave action.\n\n1. Waves approach the beach at an angle, determined by the prevailing wind direction.\n2. The swash carries sediment up the beach at this same angle.\n3. The backwash then drags sediment straight back down the beach under gravity, at right angles to the shoreline.\n4. The net result is a zigzag movement of sediment along the coast in the direction of the prevailing wind.\n\nLongshore drift supplies the sediment that builds depositional landforms such as beaches, spits and bars. Groynes are often built across the beach to interrupt the process and trap sediment, keeping beaches wide for tourism and protection.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-5-2", islandId:"g10i-04-5", front:"How do beaches form, and how do swash and backwash shape them?",
   back:"Beaches are deposits of sand and shingle between the high and low tide marks, formed where constructive waves deposit material.\n\n• Constructive waves (strong swash, weak backwash) push sediment up the beach, building it up.\n• Sandy beaches are gently sloping because the strong backwash carries fine sand back down.\n• Shingle beaches are steeper because water drains through the coarse pebbles, so backwash is weak and material stays high up.\n\nBeach features:\n• Berms — ridges of material marking high tide lines\n• Storm beach — coarse material thrown to the back by powerful storm waves\n• Runnels — channels where water drains back to the sea\n\nBeaches absorb wave energy and are a natural form of coastal protection.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-5-3", islandId:"g10i-04-5", front:"Describe how a spit forms, including its recurved end and salt marsh.",
   back:"A spit is a long, narrow ridge of sand or shingle extending from the coast into the sea.\n\nFormation:\n1. Longshore drift transports sediment along the coast.\n2. Where the coastline changes direction (e.g. at a river mouth or estuary), sediment continues to be deposited in the original direction of drift.\n3. The deposited material builds out into the sea as a spit.\n4. A change in the prevailing wind or a secondary wave direction curves the end of the spit landwards, forming a recurved end (hook).\n5. Behind the spit lies sheltered water where mud and silt accumulate, allowing a salt marsh to develop.\n\nSpits rarely cross a whole bay because river currents keep a channel open.\n\nExample: Spurn Head, Humber Estuary.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-5-4", islandId:"g10i-04-5", front:"What is a bar and how does it form?",
   back:"A bar is a ridge of sand or shingle that extends completely across a bay or inlet, joining two headlands.\n\nFormation:\n1. Longshore drift transports sediment across the mouth of a bay.\n2. If there is no river to keep a channel open, the spit can continue to grow right across the bay.\n3. The sediment eventually connects the two sides, forming a bar.\n4. Water trapped behind the bar becomes a lagoon.\n\nOver time, lagoons may silt up and develop into marshland.\n\nExample: Slapton Ley, Devon, where a shingle bar encloses a freshwater lagoon. A related landform, a tombolo, joins an island to the mainland (e.g. Chesil Beach to the Isle of Portland).", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-04-5-5", islandId:"g10i-04-5", front:"How do sand dunes form, and what is dune succession?",
   back:"Sand dunes form where there is a large supply of sand, a gentle offshore wind and an obstacle (such as driftwood or vegetation) to trap the sand.\n\nFormation:\n1. At low tide, sand dries out and is blown inland by the wind.\n2. The sand collects against obstacles, building small mounds.\n3. Pioneer plants such as marram grass colonise the sand; their roots bind it and trap more sand, so the dunes grow.\n\nDune succession (a sequence of dune types moving inland):\n• Embryo dunes — newest, nearest the sea, colonised by pioneer plants\n• Foredunes and yellow dunes — larger, stabilised by marram grass\n• Grey dunes — older, with richer soil and more plant species\n• Mature dunes — furthest inland, may support shrubs and trees\n\nSuccession shows how bare sand is gradually colonised and stabilised over time.", difficulty:2, category:"process"}
);

